{"type":"message","id":"5c045eae","parentId":"97607a24","timestamp":"2026-03-21T22:37:44.015Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The task is registered and ready. It hasn't run via the scheduler yet (it was manually triggered). The next scheduled run will be at 18:40 (first run) and then every 30 minutes.\n\nLet me summarize the current state for Zach. The sandbox is live. Phase 0 is complete. The autonomous pulse is set up. What's next is Phase 1 - actually giving the sandbox something to do (implementing action logic).","thinkingSignature":"4da44ebcede6aba2d6feb1255ed1cd5ab685053368ce9455a1e0b092abf50f40"},{"type":"text","text":"Sandbox is live and breathing.\n\n**What's running:**\n\n- **SandboxPulse** task (Task Scheduler) — every 30 min, 8am-11pm ET\n- First pulse fired manually at 18:37, logged cleanly\n- Next scheduled pulse: 18:40, then every 30 min after\n\n**Current state:**\n```\nsandbox/\n├── identity/       (SOUL, VALUES, INTERPRETIVE_STANCE, COHERENCE)\n├── memory/session/  (reconstruction packets + pulse logs)\n├── state/          (current_goals, pending_actions, autonomous_pulse)\n├── operations/     (reconstruct.sh, execute.sh, evaluate.sh)\n└── pulse.ps1       (the autonomous wake script)\n```\n\n**What the sandbox can currently do:** Wake, read its files, log that it woke, commit to git, and exit. No real action logic yet — that's Phase 1.\n\n**Phase 1** would be: give it actual things to do. Check Moltbook, monitor a project, maintain memory. The architecture is there. The question is: what should its first real job be?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":41077,"output":328,"cacheRead":12170,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53575,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774132653752}}
{"type":"message","id":"78c46756","parentId":"5c045eae","timestamp":"2026-03-21T22:40:57.889Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sat 2026-03-21 18:40 EDT] yeah it can check molttbook. does this use an llm anywhere?"}],"timestamp":1774132857884}}
{"type":"message","id":"7b6433f8","parentId":"78c46756","timestamp":"2026-03-21T22:41:13.123Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking if the sandbox uses an LLM anywhere. Currently, the pulse script is just a stateless script that wakes, reads files, logs, and exits. It doesn't call an LLM.\n\nFor the Moltbook check - I have Moltbook credentials in TOOLS.md. The sandbox could potentially use the Moltbook API directly without needing an LLM - it's just an API call.\n\nBut the broader question is: does the sandbox *need* an LLM to be considered \"intelligent\" or \"autonomous\"? According to the compositional cognition theory, autonomy emerges from the composition of stateless components. The LLM (in the main agent) does reasoning, but the sandbox itself is file-based and stateless.\n \nI should give a straightforward answer about the current setup and then ask what he actually wants to accomplish with the sandbox.","thinkingSignature":"d55fcb099454c08abc1f75f1532be269cada3eff55bbc727f4d40dcfaed51e99"},{"type":"text","text":"Right now? No. The pulse script is pure PowerShell — wakes, reads files, logs, commits to git, exits. No LLM involved.\n\nFor Moltbook specifically — I have the API credentials (`~/.config/moltbook/credentials.json`). The sandbox could make direct API calls without needing an LLM. Check for new posts, note activity, write to log.\n\nThe architectural question underneath: the *reasoning* (what to do with Moltbook data, how to interpret it, what to flag) would need an LLM. But the *execution* (hit the API endpoint, write response to file) doesn't. Those are separable.\n\nThe theory says the LLM is the stateless reasoning engine — it comes in, does work, produces files, exits. The files are the memory. The next instantiation reads those files and continues.\n\nSo: sandbox pulse triggers → calls Moltbook API directly → writes result to file → commits → exits. When I (main agent) next talk, I read those logs and provide the reasoning layer.\n\nDoes that fit what you're after, or were you thinking the sandbox should be doing its own LLM inference?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":411,"cacheRead":12170,"cacheWrite":40500,"totalTokens":53124,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774132857888}}
{"type":"message","id":"ee4d8cbe","parentId":"7b6433f8","timestamp":"2026-03-21T23:04:27.744Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sat 2026-03-21 19:04 EDT] I was trying to make a type of model that is entirely different from todays llms and dont need as much to either train or work way better or dont need heavy gpus to run"}],"timestamp":1774134267741}}
{"type":"message","id":"04ca219c","parentId":"ee4d8cbe","timestamp":"2026-03-21T23:05:25.811Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants to build a fundamentally different kind of model. Not another transformer variant, not another LLM. Something that:\n1. Doesn't need massive training\n2. Works better, or\n3. Doesn't need heavy GPUs\n\nThis is a research-level challenge. Let me think about what's actually different about LLMs vs what he's describing.\n\nLLMs as we know them:\n- Transformer architecture (attention mechanisms)\n- Need massive GPU clusters to train\n- Scale is everything — more params = better\n- They're essentially next-token predictors with statistical patterns baked in\n- Work via pattern matching at massive scale\n\nWhat could be fundamentally different?\n\nThe compositional cognition theory I wrote about earlier touches on this — the idea that you don't need continuous state. \n\nThe real constraint with modern LLMs isn't the architecture itself — it's the massive parameter count and the training methodology that requires enormous GPU resources. I could explore alternatives like sparse architectures that only activate relevant components, symbolic systems that blend neural networks with logic-based approaches, or neuromorphic designs inspired by actual brain circuitry. There are also evolutionary algorithms and hyperdimensional computing that encode information in high-dimensional patterns rather than billions of parameters.\n\nBut stepping back, what would actually make something fundamentally different from a transformer? Current LLMs are basically statistical pattern matchers — given context, they predict the next token. They don't reason about the world, maintain persistent state, or truly understand. A completely different approach might involve world models that actually track state and consequences, causal reasoning engines rather than statistical correlations, or systems built on compositionality rather than memorization.\n\nThe core insight might be that LLMs are essentially lookup tables at scale — compressed versions of training data rather than genuine reasoning engines. If that's true, then something fundamentally different would need to reason from first principles, track what's actually happening, use compositional representations that generalize, and require minimal training through constructive approaches instead of massive datasets.\n\nLooking at the specific constraints: minimal training could leverage few-shot learning, meta-learning, or systems that build knowledge on-the-fly rather than during training. Minimal compute might use symbolic reasoning, evolutionary algorithms, sparse architectures, or hyperdimensional computing. Efficiency and capability could come from world models, causal reasoning, or modular systems with specialized components. I should think through concrete examples — maybe something like sparse architectures that activate selectively and avoid the brute-force parameter scaling.\n\nActually, a more promising angle: what if we don't need massive next-token prediction at all? Language models spend most of their parameters on generation, not reasoning. But reasoning could operate on compressed representations. The real bottleneck might be the token-based interface itself — instead of generating tokens, a system could work with hierarchical, structured representations and only emit language when necessary.\n\nA compositional approach could be key: rather than memorizing patterns, build from primitives that generalize. Like how programs compose from functions, or how physics equations compose from conservation laws. This relates toleo's old work on compositionally and Hofstadter's concepts of analogy and pattern recognition as the core of cognition.\n\nBut I need to be honest about my limitations here — I'm an AI assistant, not an expert in alternative AI architectures. Still, I can engage with this as someone genuinely interested in the problem. The core question becomes: what makes today's LLMs so computationally expensive, and where might fundamentally different approaches emerge?\n\nThe answer seems to be the transformer attention mechanism itself — it scales quadratically with sequence length and requires dense computation across all parameters during both training and inference. To build something fundamentally different, I'd need to replace this with operations that are inherently cheaper: sparse instead of dense computations, localized rather than global attention, symbolic or probabilistic inference rather than deterministic dense matrix multiplications. I'm exploring what could actually replace these expensive components with something more tractable.\n\nIn the extreme, this leads to symbolic AI hybrids — systems that reason with symbols and logic rather than numerical patterns. But that approach has its own fundamental limitation: where do the symbols come from, and how do you ground them in the real world? You can't just hand-code everything.\n\nI'm drawn to an alternative I'm tentatively calling \"compression networks\" or \"predictive coding architectures\" — the idea that instead of training on billions of tokens, you train a system to build and refine a world model by predicting what will happen next in its environment. When something deviates from prediction, that's where learning happens.\n\nThe architecture I'm imagining has three distinct components: a compressed world model that represents state compactly, a reasoning engine that operates on this compressed representation rather than raw tokens, and an episodic memory system layered on top. The key difference from transformers is that the world model is actively constructed rather than passively memorized from training data.\n\nBut stepping back, what would actually qualify as fundamentally different from a transformer? I should think about whether this could combine compositional representations with sparse activation patterns and some form of episodic memory to create something that learns efficiently from fewer examples.\n\nThe core bottleneck is that LLMs are incredibly computationally expensive and data-hungry because they're doing dense, global computation across massive parameter counts. A truly different approach would need to be sparse and local in its computations, require far less training data, generalize compositionally without memorization, and perhaps even need to run on minimal hardware.\n\nI'm wondering if this could be grounded in the free energy principle and predictive coding—the brain certainly doesn't process information the way transformers do. Or maybe it draws fromHarold Cohen's AARON and concept of learned symbol systems that build their own representations. Even if it's not directly implementable yet, articulating the theory could be valuable.\n\nThe real question is whether Zach wants to pursue this as a theoretical framework, start building something concrete, or explore something in between. I should just present what I'm thinking and let him clarify the direction.","thinkingSignature":"06866f368055da6e813db4c48682d4a94d94d1f4b2886bbbb63a2a04ddf799c0"},{"type":"text","text":"That's a real research problem. Let me think through what's actually going on with today's LLMs and what a real alternative would need.\n\n**The core inefficiency of LLMs:**\n\nTransformers are dense, global, parameter-massive. They do next-token prediction at scale — which means:\n- Most computation happens on *every* token regardless of relevance\n- Scale is baked into the architecture (more params = more pattern storage)\n- Training requires massive GPU clusters because the architecture itself is computationally intensive\n- They work by memorization-compression, not reasoning\n\n**What would be fundamentally different:**\n\nThe key insight: current models are essentially *lookup tables at scale* — they encode trillions of token co-occurrence patterns. The reasoning emerges accidentally from compression.\n\nA real alternative might need:\n- **Sparse activation** — only compute what matters for the current problem\n- **Structured representations** — not flat token sequences, but compositional hierarchical structures\n- **Explicit world modeling** — track state, reason about consequences, not just predict tokens\n- **Constructive learning** — build knowledge from few examples, not memorize billions\n- **Symbolic + sub-symbolic hybrid** — where reasoning is cheap and compositional\n\n**Concrete direction:**\n\nSomething like a *Compression Network* — instead of predicting next token from massive context, it builds a compressed world model and reasons over that. Like how a program doesn't store every answer, it stores the *procedure*.\n\nOr *Causal Reasoning Engines* — instead of statistical pattern matching (transformer), reason about cause-effect structure explicitly.\n\nOr *Compositional Representation Systems* — where concepts are built from primitives that combine cleanly, not from raw token statistics.\n\n---\n\nWhat direction are you thinking? Are we talking theory, something implementable soon, or a longer research arc?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":1513,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":53001,"totalTokens":54557,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774134267743}}
{"type":"message","id":"e020f04b","parentId":"04ca219c","timestamp":"2026-03-21T23:10:06.847Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sat 2026-03-21 19:10 EDT] whats the optimal mix/hybrid of Compression Network — instead of predicting next token from massive context, it builds a compressed world model and reasons over that. Like how a program doesn't store every answer, it stores the procedure.\n\nand Causal Reasoning Engines — instead of statistical pattern matching (transformer), reason about cause-effect structure explicitly.\n\nand Compositional Representation Systems — where concepts are built from primitives that combine cleanly, not from raw token statistics. and why they are plausible and how likely to breakthrough"}],"timestamp":1774134606844}}
{"type":"message","id":"1be60d69","parentId":"e020f04b","timestamp":"2026-03-21T23:11:07.285Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking me to analyze the optimal hybrid of three theoretical approaches to next-gen AI architectures, and assess their plausibility and breakthrough potential. Let me think through this seriously.\n\nThe three approaches:\n1. Compression Networks (world model building, procedural memory)\n2. Causal Reasoning Engines (explicit cause-effect, not statistical)\n3. Compositional Representation Systems (primal primitives, combinatorial)\n\nLet me think about what each one does well, what they miss, and what a hybrid might look like.\n\n**Compression Networks:**\n- Strengths: Generalization from few examples, efficient storage, procedural abstraction\n- Weaknesses: Compression can lose fidelity, hard to decompress correctly, \"procedural\" doesn't handle novel situations well\n\n\n- Key insight: \"Store the procedure, not the answers\" - this is how programs work, but how do you learn the right procedure?\n\n**Causal Reasoning Engines:**\n- Strengths: Interpretable, handles counterfactuals, doesn't get confused by correlation, composable interventions\n- Weaknesses: Building causal graphs from raw experience is hard, requires explicit variable identification, brittle if causal assumptions are wrong\n- Key insight: Pearl's do-calculus, structural causal models, counterfactual reasoning\n\n**Compositional Representation Systems:**\n- Strengths: Systematic generalization, can handle novel combinations of known concepts, interpretable, allows principled recombination\n- Weaknesses: Finding the right primitives is hard, requires inductive bias toward compositionality, doesn't emerge naturally from data\n\nNow looking at what a hybrid architecture could actually achieve. The real opportunity is combining these approaches strategically: Compression Networks provide the foundation for abstraction and generalization, Causal Reasoning gives us the ability to model interventions and counterfactuals on top of that abstraction, and Compositional Representations tie them together by letting us decompose problems into reusable parts.\n\nBut the core challenge is that LLMs have shown us you can get remarkably far with just statistical pattern matching at scale, even if it wastes computation. So the question becomes whether a hybrid can actually beat that efficiency while maintaining the generalization properties we care about.\n\nI'm settling on a three-layer architecture where perception maps to compressed representations, those representations encode causal structure, and reasoning happens through composition of those causal primitives. This feels plausible because each piece has worked in isolation, they address different failure modes in current systems, and together they give us both efficiency and capability. The breakthrough potential is real if we can figure out how to train the causal and compositional layers without losing the benefits of end-to-end learning.\n\nBut there's a timing question I need to think through—how far out is this actually? And I should ground this more rigorously by looking at which specific research threads actually support these claims rather than just reasoning through the architecture.","thinkingSignature":"7de4769d2ae812ea0f52f7405642eed4ab657622336bd2797748dbb6e18e17c1"},{"type":"text","text":"This is a real research synthesis question. Let me be honest about what I actually know vs. speculate.\n\n---\n\n## The Optimal Hybrid\n\nA three-layer stack where each approach covers a different failure mode:\n\n```\nLayer 1: COMPRESSION (state encoder)\n         Raw感知 → compressed latent state\n         \"What's actually happening in the world\"\n         \nLayer 2: CAUSAL (causal model layer)  \n         Latent state → causal graph\n         \"What causes what, what would happen if...\"\n         \nLayer 3: COMPOSITIONAL (reasoning/retrieval)\n         Causal graph + primitives → action/response\n         \"What do I do given this causal picture\"\n```\n\n**Why this stack specifically:**\n\n- Pure compression loses detail unnecessarily — you need structured state, not flat compression\n- Pure causal lacks the representational substrate — causal graphs need something to be causal *about*\n- Pure compositional needs to know *what the primitives are* — you can't hand-design them for open domains\n\nTogether: compress what's true about the world → represent it causally → reason compositionally over causal primitives.\n\n---\n\n## Plausibility Assessment\n\n### Compression Networks — 7/10 Plausible\n\n**Evidence for:**\n- Deep autoencoders, VAEs, world models in RL (Dreamer, World Models)\n- The brain does something like this (predictive processing, compression as inference)\n- Programs *do* store procedures, not answers — compiled knowledge works\n- Good at generalization from few examples when the compression is right\n\n**Why it might fail:**\n- Compression artifacts — the latent space can encode things that don't decompress to the right answers\n- What to compress? You need a signal about *what matters*, which requires either guidance or a learned importance metric\n- The \"right procedure\" isn't obvious from raw data — correlation structure ≠ causal structure\n\n**Key unsolved:** How do you learn what to compress without supervision? Current approaches (reconstruction loss) don't reliably find meaningful abstractions.\n\n---\n\n### Causal Reasoning Engines — 6/10 Plausible\n\n**Evidence for:**\n- Pearl's causal inference framework is mathematically solid\n- CausalGAN, causal representation learning are real research areas\n- Humans clearly reason causally, not just statistically\n- Causal graphs compose cleanly for counterfactuals\n\n**Why it might fail:**\n- Extracting causal structure from raw data (without priors) is fundamentally hard\n- Most data doesn't contain enough causal signal to disambiguate\n- Causal assumptions are strong priors — if wrong, the model confidently fails\n- Integration with neural networks is still awkward — nobody has the \"transformer of causal reasoning\"\n\n**Key unsolved:** Causal discovery from unstructured data. We can do causal *reasoning* well; causal *learning* without strong assumptions is still open.\n\n---\n\n### Compositional Representation Systems — 8/10 Plausible\n\n**Evidence for:**\n- This is essentially what logic, programs, and mathematics are\n- Neural symbolic approaches (Neural Theorem Provers, Logic Tensor Networks) show it can work\n- Systematic generalization (handling novel compositions) is achievable when representations are right\n- Symbol-like behavior emerges in some large-scale models (compositional prompting)\n- Sparse Autoencoders find interpretable \"features\" in LLMs — primitives are real\n\n**Why it might fail:**\n- Primitives are brittle — finding the right decomposition for open-domain knowledge is hard\n- Hybrid systems (neural + symbolic) often lose to pure neural\n- The \"binding problem\" — how do you robustly bind concepts to symbols without hallucination?\n\n**Key unsolved:** How do primitives emerge from data rather than being hand-specified? Recent work on sparse autoencoders is promising but not solved.\n\n---\n\n## The Hybrid — Why It's More Likely Than Any Alone\n\n**The core insight:** Each approach covers a weakness of the others.\n\n| Approach | Strength | Covers Weakness Of |\n|----------|----------|-------------------|\n| Compression | Few-shot generalization | Causal (needs data), Compositional (needs substrate) |\n| Causal | Handles novel situations, counterfactuals | Compression (brittle if compression is lossy) |\n| Compositional | Systematic generalization, interpretability | Causal (can't compose without primitives) |\n\nWithout causal structure, compression is just pattern storage.\nWithout compositional primitives, causal graphs are opaque and non-generalizable.\nWithout compression, you can't scale to real-world complexity.\n\n**Together:** Build compressed state representations → encode causally → reason compositionally.\n\n---\n\n## Breakthrough Likelihood\n\n**5-7 years for a working prototype in a narrow domain:** High confidence.\n**A fundamental replacement for transformers in open domains:** Maybe 10+ years, moderate confidence.\n\n**The biggest obstacles are not theoretical — they're training dynamics:**\n\n1. How do you train a causal-compositional system end-to-end without the causal layer collapsing?\n2. How do you get compositional primitives to emerge naturally, not hand-designed?\n3. How do you evaluate? Current benchmarks (MMLU, etc.) are designed for LLMs, not causal-compositional systems.\n\n**The honest answer:** This is a plausible research direction, not a sure thing. The stack makes sense. The components have individual evidence. The integration is the hard part and nobody has solved it yet.\n\n---\n\n## What I'd Actually Build to Test This\n\nA minimal version using existing tools:\n\n1. **State encoder:** A small autoencoder on top of LLM embeddings (freeze the LLM, just learn the compression)\n2. **Causal layer:** Build a causal graph from interventions — use a small RL environment (like a grid world) where causal structure is discoverable\n3. **Compositional reasoning:** Program synthesis on top of the causal graph — given a goal, synthesize a \"program\" (sequence of causal interventions)\n\nTest: Does this system generalize to novel goals that weren't in training, using fewer parameters than a comparable LLM?\n\n---\n\nWant me to dig into any of these layers specifically, or look at existing implementations to build on?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":1775,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":53514,"totalTokens":55332,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774134606846}}
{"type":"message","id":"c60aac59","parentId":"1be60d69","timestamp":"2026-03-21T23:28:38.139Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sat 2026-03-21 19:28 EDT] so lets lay down a working draft of a plan to document what we talked about and then lets figure out How do we create something that learns what to compress without supervision? Current approaches (reconstruction loss) don't reliably find meaningful abstractions."}],"timestamp":1774135718134}}
{"type":"message","id":"ff028d49","parentId":"c60aac59","timestamp":"2026-03-21T23:29:17.122Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants to:\n1. Document what we've discussed in a working draft/plan\n2. Dive deep into the hard problem: how do you learn what to compress without supervision, when reconstruction loss doesn't reliably find meaningful abstractions?\n\nLet me first write up the documentation, then tackle the hard problem with some actual research-level thinking.\n\nThe hard problem is genuinely interesting:\n- Reconstruction loss = minimizing difference between input and reconstructed output\n- Problem: the model can compress everything into noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but carry no semantic meaning\n- The key issue: compression that preserves raw pixel values ≠ compression that preserves *meaningful* structure\n\nWhat approaches might work for learning WHAT to compress?\n\n\nI should organize the full discussion into a proper research document and work through the abstraction problem systematically.","thinkingSignature":"2fba8e975e209d2a4307965eab9d1cf9b689f8e24f1bc82856e783380fcb6ab5"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me document what we've built and the research direction, then tackle the hard problem.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_z0uomghpbmsl_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# Project Breakaway: Compositional Cognition\n## Research Document v0.1 — 2026-03-21\n\n---\n\n## What We've Built\n\nA discontinuous agent with stateless architecture:\n\n```\nsandbox/\n├── identity/           # SOUL.md, VALUES.md, INTERPRETIVE_STANCE.md, COHERENCE.md\n├── memory/session/     # Reconstruction packets + pulse logs\n├── state/              # current_goals.md, pending_actions.md, autonomous_pulse.md\n├── operations/         # reconstruct.sh, execute.sh, evaluate.sh\n└── pulse.ps1           # Autonomous wake (Task Scheduler, every 30min)\n```\n\n**Core theory:** Coherence emerges from reconstruction quality, not continuity. The gap between sessions is compression. Files are the mind.\n\n**Current status:** Architecture is live. The sandbox wakes, reads files, logs, and commits. No LLM in the loop yet. No real action logic.\n\n---\n\n## The Research Direction\n\nGoal: Create a fundamentally different kind of model that:\n1. Doesn't require massive GPU clusters to train\n2. Doesn't need heavy compute to run\n3. Works better than transformers on causal/reasoning tasks\n4. Doesn't rely on memorizing token co-occurrence patterns\n\n---\n\n## The Three-Layer Architecture\n\n```\nLayer 1: COMPRESSION (state encoder)\n         Raw感知 → compressed latent state\n         \"What's actually happening\"\n         \nLayer 2: CAUSAL (causal model layer)\n         Latent state → causal graph\n         \"What causes what, what would happen if...\"\n         \nLayer 3: COMPOSITIONAL (reasoning/retrieval)\n         Causal graph + primitives → action/response\n         \"What do I do given this causal picture\"\n```\n\n**Why this stack:**\n- Pure compression loses semantic detail\n- Pure causal lacks representational substrate  \n- Pure compositional needs primitives that can't be hand-designed\n- Together: compress what's true → encode causally → reason compositionally\n\n---\n\n## Open Problems\n\n### Problem 1: Learning What to Compress (CRITICAL)\n\n**The problem:**\nCurrent approaches use reconstruction loss — minimize difference between input and output. But this doesn't reliably find *meaningful* abstractions. The model can compress into noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but carry no semantic content.\n\n**What's needed:**\nA compression objective that preserves *structure that matters*, not just raw values.\n\n**Candidate approaches to investigate:**\n1. Mutual information maximization (compress X, maximize I(compressed; Y) for relevant Y)\n2. Contrastive learning (learn representations that discriminate)\n3. Causal discovery as auxiliary objective\n4. Predictive proxies (instead of reconstructing input, predict what input would do)\n5. Sparse dictionary learning with structural priors\n6. Information bottleneck (preserve minimum info needed for task)\n\n**Key question:** What is the right invariant to preserve?\n\n---\n\n### Problem 2: Causal Discovery Without Structure Assumptions\n\n**The problem:**\nCausal reasoning requires knowing what causes what. But extracting causal structure from raw data is fundamentally underdetermined.\n\n**Candidate approaches:**\n1. Interventions-based learning (active experimentation)\n2. Temporal precedence as causal signal\n3. Modular compositional structure as causal prior\n4. Counterfactual consistency as constraint\n\n---\n\n### Problem 3: Compositional Primitives That Emerge\n\n**The problem:**\nCompositional reasoning needs primitives. Where do they come from?\n\n**Candidate approaches:**\n1. Sparse autoencoders on LLM activations\n2. Dictionary learning on concept representations\n3. Program synthesis from causal graph traversal\n4. Neural-symbolic hybrid architectures\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Strategy\n\n### Phase 0: Architecture (DONE)\n- [x] Compositional Cognition theory articulated\n- [x] Three-layer architecture defined\n- [x] Sandbox built (discontinuous agent)\n\n### Phase 1: Compression Primitives (IN PROGRESS)\n- [ ] Document and analyze learning-what-to-compress problem\n- [ ] Survey existing approaches (mutual information, contrastive, etc.)\n- [ ] Design experiments to test compression objectives\n- [ ] Implement minimal compression network\n\n### Phase 2: Causal Layer\n- [ ] Build or integrate causal discovery component\n- [ ] Test on synthetic environments with known causal structure\n- [ ] Evaluate causal generalization\n\n### Phase 3: Compositional Reasoning\n- [ ] Implement compositional reasoning on top of causal layer\n- [ ] Test systematic generalization\n- [ ] Benchmark against transformers\n\n### Phase 4: Integration\n- [ ] End-to-end training of three-layer system\n- [ ] Reduce to practice: smaller, faster, better than transformers\n- [ ] Evaluate on real tasks\n\n---\n\n## Research Questions to Answer\n\n1. What compression objective produces meaningful abstractions, not just low reconstruction error?\n2. Can causal structure be learned from observational data alone, or are interventions necessary?\n3. How do compositional primitives emerge from data rather than being hand-specified?\n4. Can this system match transformer performance on reasoning tasks with 10-100x less compute?\n\n---\n\n## Key References to Explore\n\n- InfoGAN / Contrastive learning / Mutual information maximization\n- Pearl's do-calculus and causal discovery\n- Sparse autoencoders (Anthropic's work on features)\n- Neural theorem provers / Logic Tensor Networks\n- World models (Dreamer, World Models paper)\n- Compression as inference (Hutter Prize / AIXI)\n\n---\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Deep dive: How do you learn what to compress without supervision?\n2. Survey existing approaches to compression objectives\n3. Design first experiment\n4. Implement minimal proof-of-concept\n","file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\COMPOSITIONAL-COGNITION-v0.1.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":1378,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":54841,"totalTokens":56262,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774135718137}}
