{"type":"message","id":"bde09cc6","parentId":"25a51936","timestamp":"2026-03-21T23:30:59.437Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me tackle the hard problem: how do you learn what to compress without supervision, when reconstruction loss doesn't work?\n\nLet me think through this genuinely:\n\n**The core problem with reconstruction loss:**\nThe issue is that reconstruction loss only cares about preserving information, not about what information is *meaningful*. A trivial solution: identity function (reconstruct perfectly, learn nothing useful). The model finds bypasses — it can memorize the input or store noise that happens to reconstruct well.\n\n**What makes an abstraction \"meaningful\"?**\n1. It generalizes — compresses patterns, not specific instances\n2. It captures invariances — what stays the same across transformations\n\n\n3. It supports downstream tasks — compressed representation predicts something useful\n4. It reveals causal structure — not just correlation\n5. It composes — primitives can recombine into novel situations\n\n**The key insight:** Mutual information maximization between compressed representation and something that *matters* — either future inputs (predictive), downstream rewards (RL), or structural invariants. This is what separates mere compression from learning useful abstractions.\n\n**Concrete approaches:**\n\n1. **Predictive Compression (InfoGAN / CPC):**\nInstead of reconstructing the input, I train the compressor to predict future representations. This naturally selects for stable, generalizable features rather than noise-specific details, similar to how contrastive predictive coding works.\n\n2. **Contrastive Compression:**\nThe compressor learns by pushing similar inputs together and pulling dissimilar ones apart in latent space, encouraging it to capture meaningful structure.\n\n3. **Information Bottleneck:**\nThis formalizes the intuition by balancing reconstruction quality against compression size, using a Lagrange multiplier to control the tradeoff.\n\n4. **Causal Discovery as Regularizer:**\nI incorporate causal structure directly into the compression objective, forcing the latent space to encode causal relationships rather than just correlational patterns.\n\n5. **Variational Inference with Structured Priors:**\nInstead of a generic prior over latents, I enforce structured constraints like sparsity or modularity so the compressor discovers disentangled representations that match how the world actually decomposes.\n\n6. **Disagreement-Based Compression:**\nMultiple hypotheses about what to compress will disagree on which features matter, and this disagreement itself signals important structure that the model should capture.\n\n7. **Task-Agnostic vs. Task-Specific Compression:**\nI could optimize for human-judged similarity as an unsupervised proxy, though the fundamental constraint is that perfect compression without inductive bias is impossible—the real question is which inductive biases actually produce useful representations rather than just low-error reconstructions.\n\n8. **Minimum Description Length as Supervision:**\nThe key insight is that good abstractions are those that compress well across an ensemble of instances, not just one specific example. I should formalize this around the MDL principle and how it distinguishes good abstractions from mere memorization, then think through what the optimal approach actually is.\n\nThe core issue with reconstruction loss isn't that it fails in general—it's that it fails to capture semantics. The compressor will happily encode pixel-level noise or instance-specific details rather than the invariant structure that actually matters. Information-theoretic approaches like mutual information maximization offer a way out, though they come with their own statistical challenges.\n\nContrastive methods work well but require good negative samples. Causal discovery is promising because causal structure is inherently compressible, but it demands strong assumptions about temporal ordering or the ability to intervene. The real question is what inductive bias actually guides compression toward meaningful abstractions rather than trivial solutions. Human-designed structure in the architecture or loss function seems unavoidable.\n\nI'm drawn to the idea that *invariance* is what distinguishes semantics from noise—concepts that stay constant across transformations are inherently compressible. The key insight is that semantic information (what you want to compress) differs from statistical information (what reconstruction loss preserves). The semantic layer is the redundancy across instances; noise is instance-specific and incompressible. A compression objective that minimizes description length while maximizing semantic information would naturally capture what's actually meaningful.\n\nThe hard problem is that we can't directly observe which information is semantic. I need to explore approaches like causal emergence (where macro-level descriptions compress better than micro-level ones) or competence models that predict what an agent needs to know to achieve goals. Sparse representations might help—most features are noise, so a sparse encoder that activates only meaningful features could be more robust. Ultimately, compression should be evaluated by downstream task performance, not reconstruction quality alone, since we only know if compression worked when we see if the decompressed information actually helps.","thinkingSignature":"c863e3409953f964adf48da59094fa4fd26656eacb88d9c3978226912efcb2c7"},{"type":"text","text":"Now the hard problem. Let me write up the deep analysis:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_50akcegkuvhj_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# Problem: Learning What to Compress Without Supervision\n## Technical Analysis — 2026-03-21\n\n---\n\n## Why Reconstruction Loss Fails\n\nReconstruction loss minimizes: L = ||x - D(E(x))||²\n\n**The fundamental problem:** This objective has a trivial local minimum — the identity function. The model can:\n1. Pass input through unchanged (no compression at all)\n2. Learn noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but encode nothing useful\n3. Store instance-specific details instead of generalizable patterns\n\n**What goes wrong:** Reconstruction loss optimizes for *preserving information*, not for *extracting meaningful structure*. These are fundamentally different objectives.\n\nThe information-theoretic version (minimize mutual information between input and compressed representation) has the opposite trivial minimum — compress everything to a constant, which preserves no information but has minimal mutual information.\n\nBoth naive objectives fail because they don't encode *what should be preserved*.\n\n---\n\n## The Core Insight: Semantic vs Statistical Information\n\n**Statistical information:** Raw redundancy in data. \"These 1000 images share pixel pattern X.\" Captured by reconstruction loss.\n\n**Semantic information:** What the data *means*, causally and functionally. \"Object X causes Y to happen.\" NOT captured by reconstruction loss.\n\n**The key asymmetry:**\n- Semantic information is a SUBSET of statistical information\n- Most statistical structure is not semantic\n- Compression that preserves only semantic information requires knowing what semantics matter\n\n**Implication:** You can't extract semantics from data alone. You need an inductive bias that tells the compressor *what kind of semantics to look for*.\n\n---\n\n## Candidate Approaches\n\n### Approach 1: Predictive Compression (CPC / InfoGAN)\n\n**Idea:** Instead of reconstructing x, predict what x will be — or predict a property of x.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = -log P(semantic_property | E(x))\n```\n\nThe compressor learns to encode whatever predicts the property well. If the property is well-chosen (e.g., \"this text's continuation\"), the compressor finds meaningful structure.\n\n**Variants:**\n- Contrastive Predictive Coding (CPC): predict future representations\n- InfoGAN: maximize mutual information between latents and property\n- PIRL (Predicting Instance-level Labels): contrastive across transformations\n\n**Why it works:** Prediction is a selection pressure. To predict well, you must encode what's invariant across the prediction task. The prediction target acts as the semantic filter.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Prediction of *what*? If you predict wrong properties, you learn wrong structure\n- The prediction task itself encodes what matters — but how do you choose it unsupervised?\n- Contrastive methods need good negative samples — hard in continuous domains\n\n**Verdict:** Promising but circular — the prediction target is the real inductive bias.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 2: Information Bottleneck with Semantic Regularizer\n\n**Idea:** Minimize description length while maximizing a semantic objective.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = β * I(E(x); x) - I(E(x); y_semantic)\n```\n\nWhere y_semantic is something that signals \"this matters.\" In practice: temporal proximity (things close in time share causal structure), or downstream task signals.\n\n**Problems:**\n- y_semantic is exactly what we're trying to find\n- β tuning is unstable — too low = memorize, too high = lose everything\n- Information estimation in high dimensions is intractable\n\n**Verdict:** Theoretically clean, practically intractable without a semantic signal.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 3: Causal Discovery as Compression\n\n**Idea:** Causal structure IS compressible structure. Things that are causally related are statistically dependent in specific ways. Finding causal structure means finding what's semantically related.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Causal mechanisms are independent (modular)\n- Causal relations are invariant across interventions\n- Statistical dependencies that are invariant are likely causal\n\n```python\n# Simplified causal compression\nfor each potential causal relation (X → Y):\n    if P(Y | do(X)) ≠ P(Y):  # X causes Y\n        encode causal relation in latent\n```\n\n**Why it's promising:** Causal structure is exactly the kind of semantic structure we want. Interventions change distributions in predictable ways. Invariance across interventions is a detectable signal.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Causal discovery from passive observation is fundamentally limited\n- Without interventions (active experimentation), you can't distinguish causation from confounds\n- Most data doesn't contain enough causal signal without strong assumptions\n\n**Verdict:** Best theoretical match, but requires either interventions or strong priors. Partial solution: use environment affordances to determine what can be intervened on.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 4: Compression as Program Induction\n\n**Idea:** Instead of compressing into raw vectors, compress into programs. Programs that generate the data concisely are inherently more compressible than programs that just store it.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Learn a program that generates the data\n- The program's complexity is the description length\n- Good abstractions = short programs that generate many instances\n\nThis is essentially Minimum Description Length (MDL) + program synthesis.\n\n**Why it's promising:** A program that generates 1000 images of \"dog\" from a 50-line generator is more compressible than storing all 1000 images. The generator captures semantic structure (what makes a dog a dog).\n\n**Problems:**\n- Program synthesis is hard and search is huge\n- Discrete search + gradient learning = gradient estimation challenges\n- Most data isn't generated by simple programs\n\n**Verdict:** Theoretically compelling, computationally intractable at scale. Good for structured domains (math, logic) not raw perception.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 5: Sparse Dictionary Learning with Invariance Constraints\n\n**Idea:** Most features in raw data are noise. A sparse encoder that must use few active features to represent data will naturally select for features that carry the most information.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = ||x - D(E(x))||² + λ * ||E(x)||₁ + invariance_regularizer\n```\n\nWhere `invariance_regularizer` encourages features to be invariant across transformations.\n\n**Variants:**\n- k-SVD and classical sparse coding\n- ISTA/FISTA networks\n- Sparse autoencoders (SAEs) — Anthropic has shown these find interpretable features\n\n**Why it might work:** Sparsity forces selection. A feature that fires on every input is useless — the model must find features that fire discriminatively. Meaningful features tend to be sparse.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Sparsity alone doesn't guarantee semantic meaningfulness\n- Learned features can be \"arbitrary but sparse\" without being interpretable\n- Need additional constraints to push toward semantic structure\n\n**Verdict:** SAEs are empirically promising (Anthropic's work) but we don't fully understand why they work or when they fail.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 6: Emergent Abstractions Through Self-Supervision on Behavioral Goals\n\n**Idea:** Don't compress raw input. Compress what an agent needs to *act successfully*.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = ||reward - V(E(state))||²\n```\n\nThe compressor learns to encode whatever predicts value/reward best. Reward = what matters to the agent. This is world model learning in RL.\n\n**Variants:**\n- DreamerV3 / World Models: compress pixel inputs into latent world model, plan in latent space\n- Successor representations: predict future states weighted by reward\n- Empowerment (maximize mutual information between action and future state)\n\n**Why it works:** Reward is the semantic signal. What predicts reward is what matters. The compressor's job becomes \"encode whatever predicts outcomes that matter.\"\n\n**Problems:**\n- Reward is task-specific — doesn't generalize across tasks\n- Reward crafting is itself an inductive bias\n- What about tasks where reward is sparse or delayed?\n\n**Verdict:** Best practical approach for embodied agents. But not task-agnostic.\n\n---\n\n## The Key Insight: Invariance as Semantic Signal\n\n**What makes an abstraction \"meaningful\"?**\n→ It is INVARIANT across transformations while being USEFUL for a goal.\n\n**Examples:**\n- \"Object permanence\" is invariant across spatial transformations of the object\n- \"Causality\" is invariant across interventions (if X causes Y, do(X) changes Y predictably)\n- \"Dog-ness\" is invariant across pose/lighting/viewpoint transformations\n\n**Implication:** Find the compression that is INVARIANT across transformations, and you likely have a semantic abstraction.\n\n**Formalization:**\n```\nFind E(x) that maximizes: I(E(x); invariant_property) * downstream_utility\n```\n\nWhere `invariant_property` is something like \"this remains constant under transformation T.\"\n\n**The problem:** `invariant_property` is exactly what we need to find. But: temporal continuity is observable (things near in time tend to be causally related), and behavioral affordances are learnable (agents can learn what can be intervened on).\n\n---\n\n## Proposed Research Direction: Invariance-Maximizing Compression\n\n**Core idea:** The compressor learns to represent what's invariant across:\n1. Temporal neighbors (things that stay the same across time)\n2. Spatial/temporal transformations (viewpoints, rotations, small changes)\n3. Noise/perturbations that don't affect semantics\n\n**Architecture sketch:**\n```\nInput x → Encoder E → Latent z\n                  ↑\n      Invariance loss: maximize ||E(x) - E(T(x))|| small\n                       for transformation T\n                  ↓\n      Predictor P: z → downstream prediction\n                  ↓\n      Utility loss: maximize prediction accuracy\n```\n\n**Why this might work:**\n- Invariance forces extraction of what doesn't change — semantic content\n- Utility ensures what you extract actually matters\n- Together: encode what's both invariant AND useful\n\n**Remaining question:** What is \"useful\"? For task-agnostic learning, we need a task-agnostic utility signal. One candidate: predictive model accuracy (CPC-style). Another: maximizing empowerment (influence over future states).\n\n---\n\n## What Actually Matters (The Synthesis)\n\n**The honest answer:** You can't fully escape needing an inductive bias. The question is WHERE the bias enters:\n\n1. **Architecture:** What structure does the compressor have? (e.g., sparse = better features)\n2. **Loss function:** What objective guides learning? (reconstruction → prediction → contrastive → causal)\n3. **Data:** What training distribution? (temporal continuity, interventions, goal-directed)\n4. **Priors:** What constraints on the latent space? (sparsity, modularity, causal structure)\n\n**Best bet for breakthrough:**\nCausal discovery + sparse representations + goal-directed environment interaction.\n\nThe causal structure tells you what's semantically related.\nThe sparse representation ensures you can't encode everything — must select.\nThe goal-directed interaction provides the signal for what matters.\n\n**This suggests:** Build a system in an environment where:\n- Interventions are possible (agent can act and see consequences)\n- Temporal structure is rich (succession, causation observable)\n- Goals are learnable (not hardcoded reward)\n\nLet the system discover causal structure through interaction.\nLet the compressor encode causal structure in sparse latents.\nLet the reasoner compose over causal primitives.\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. Can causal structure be learned from passive observation, or are interventions strictly necessary?\n2. What is the minimal inductive bias needed for semantic compression?\n3. Can we combine multiple compression objectives (invariant + predictive + causal) in a single training signal?\n4. How do you evaluate compression quality without downstream tasks?\n5. Is there a fundamental limit on unsupervised semantic compression?\n\n---\n\n## References to Explore\n\n- **InfoGAN** (Chen et al., 2016) — mutual information as regularization\n- **Contrastive Predictive Coding** (Oord et al., 2018) — future prediction as compression\n- **Causal Discovery** (Pearl, Spirtes, Glymour) — do-calculus, PC algorithm\n- **Sparse Autoencoders** (Anthropic, 2024) — monosemantic features in LLMs\n- **World Models / Dreamer** (Hafner et al., 2019, 2023) — world model for RL\n- **Minimum Description Length** (Rissanen, 1978) — compression = learning\n- **Invariant Risk Minimization** (Arjovsky et al., 2019) — invariance as generalization\n","file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\COMPRESSION-LEARNING-WITHOUT-SUPERVISION.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":44141,"output":3481,"cacheRead":12170,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":59792,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774135757136}}
